content_chunks.content: This digital course provides knowledge and practical experience at three levels (basic, intermediate, and advanced) in developing and applying composite materials. The course objectives are the following: to deliver into the composite materials technology and characterization; to familiarize with principles of structural design, materials characterization, and choice of constituents; to relate the time-dependent changes of materials properties and internal structure of composite with structural resistance. The course focuses on efficiently utilizing and combining advanced and recycled materials to reduce the volume of traditional materials, reducing natural resource demands. The application examples include fiber-reinforced cement-based and polymeric composites, recycled and biodegradable polymers, and thin-walled metal components in different combinations. The course also describes additive manufacturing principles as the most innovative, tailorable, and waste-diminishing fabrication technique.

Composite materials technology for sustainable structural applications and advanced manufacturing - this course delivers comprehensive expertise in developing and applying fiber-reinforced, polymeric, and recycled composite materials for environmentally conscious construction. Students master materials characterization techniques, structural design principles, and additive manufacturing processes that enable waste-reducing fabrication methods. The curriculum covers long-term performance analysis, material aging processes, and 3D printing technologies that optimize composite efficiency while reducing natural resource consumption. Graduates emerge skilled in creating innovative composite solutions that combine advanced materials with recycled components, implementing sustainable structural systems that minimize environmental impact while maximizing performance through advanced material engineering and waste-diminishing fabrication techniques.
